the ulnar artery site, there is rapid capillary refill.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pairs of structures is most likely to have been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Median nerve and ulnar artery","Median nerve and radial artery","Radial nerve and radial artery","Radial nerve and ulnar artery","Ulnar nerve and radial artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve and radial artery\u003C/strong\u003E. To understand this, it is important to understand the basic anatomy and function of each nerve along with the function of the Allen test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (nerve root C5/C6-T1):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation: flexor and pronator of the anterior compartment of the forearm, the LOAF muscles of the hand (lateral two lumbricals, opponens pollicis, abductor pollicis brevis, flexor pollicis brevis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation: the lateral aspect of the palm, lateral 3.5 fingers of the palmar surface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve \u003C/strong\u003E(nerve root C8-T1):\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation: intrinsic muscles and muscles of the anterior forearm for wrist flexion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation: medial 1.5 fingers of the palmar and dorsal of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003E(nerve root C5-T1):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation: innervates the triceps and the extensors of the forearm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation: innervates the skin of the posterior forearm, lateral aspect of the dorsum of the hand and the dorsal surface of the lateral 3.5 digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe flexor carpi radialis muscle lies in between the median nerve and ulnar artery, and it is critical for the flexion and abduction of the wrist. A laceration of this will result in failure to flex the wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Allen test\u00a0assesses for collateral flow to the hands. In this case it is evident that the ulnar artery is still functional as it refills with the release of the ulnar artery site. With this information and the fact that there is decreased capillary refill suggesting decreased perfusion, it is highly likely that the radial artery has been damaged, especially with its proximity to the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The median nerve supplies the majority of sensation of the palmar aspect of the palm"],"references":["The median nerve [Internet]. TeachMeAnatomy. [cited 2022Oct29]. Available from: https://teachmeanatomy.info/upper-limb/nerves/median-nerve/","The radial nerve [Internet]. TeachMeAnatomy. [cited 2022Oct29]. Available from: https://teachmeanatomy.info/upper-limb/nerves/radial-nerve/","The Ulnar Nerve [Internet]. TeachMeAnatomy. [cited 2022Oct29]. Available from: https://teachmeanatomy.info/upper-limb/nerves/ulnar-nerve/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84729"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1322"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84729"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-11T10:12:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T10:12:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1322"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"10